3.4 Computation Model

We consider the inference latency and the energy consumption of each sample. The overhead for collecting states of the UEs in each time frame is ignored, as the state information is usually negligible compared with the ofÔ¨Çoading data. In the worst case, the extra latency at the server is only a small constant, which does not affect the optimization results. Here we still take UE n as an example, and suppose that the size of compressed intermediate feature is fn bits at partitioning point bn. When n = 0, fn denotes the size of the original input sample. We assume a powerful edge server, i.e., all received tasks can be Ô¨Ånished with negligible latency, and omit the latency at the edge end. Similar settings can be found in previous works [14]. Hence, the inference latency of a single sample is composed of three terms: the local inference latency tfn, the feature compression latency tcn, and the data transmission latency ttn. The local inference latency tfn and the feature compression latency tcn can be collected on device. Based on the communication model, the data transmission latency is:

ttn

