If there are two policies œÄ1 and œÄ2 that satisfy f2(œÄ1) > f2(œÄ2), we aim to prove that f1(œÄ1) > f1(œÄ2). We consider two cases: 1) K(œÄ1) ‚â• K(œÄ2); 2) K(œÄ1) < K(œÄ2).
For case 1), it is obvious that f1(œÄ1) > f1(œÄ2). For case 2), we can obtain that T (œÄ1) > T (œÄ2), since K(œÄ) is the expected number of completed tasks in one time frame. Thus we have A(œÄ1) > A(œÄ2), and for f1(¬∑), we have:

f1(œÄ1) ‚àí f1(œÄ2) = (A(œÄ1) ‚àí A(œÄ2)) + Œ≤(B(œÄ1) ‚àí B(œÄ2)),
where B(œÄ1) ‚àí B(œÄ2) denotes the extra energy used for completing all tasks using policy œÄ2. This value is upper bounded since the energy consumption of the local inference and the feature compression is constant, and the transmit power is upper bounded. Thus there must exist a small Œ≤ that ensures f1(œÄ1) > f1(œÄ2). According to the analysis in the above two cases, we conclude that minimizing the objective function of problem (P2) can guarantee the decrease of the objective function of problem (P1) when Œ≤ is small.
Discussion. Problem (P2) converts the sum of tasks into the sum of time frames, so that the problem is in accordance with the form of cumulative reward in DRL. In practice,

the improvement of K(œÄ) can usually decrease the overall energy consumption B(œÄ). Thus generally a large Œ≤ can also
guarantee the validity of Theorem 1.

4.3 MDP Formulation

An MDP depicts the interaction between the DRL agent
and the environment and can be represented by a tuple (S; A; P ; r), where S is a set of states, A is a set of actions, P : S √ó A √ó S ‚Üí R is a probability distribution that depicts the system dynamics, and r : S √ó A √ó S ‚Üí R is the reward.
We Ô¨Årst deÔ¨Åne state st of the MDP, where t denotes the t-th decision time frame. State st consists of four parts: the left task number kt, the left local computation time lt, the left ofÔ¨Çoading data size nt, and the distance from UEs to the edge server d. That is, st = {kt, lt, nt, d}, where kt contains the left uncompleted task number of each UE at time t,
which may guide the system to assign more resources to the UEs that have more uncompleted tasks; lt is the left time of
completing the local inference and the feature compression of current half-completed tasks; nt is the size of left data to be ofÔ¨Çoaded of these tasks; and the distance d is , which
remains unchanged in one episode. We then deÔ¨Åne action at at time t, given by at =
{bt, ct, pt}, where bt is the partitioning point of each UE, ct is the ofÔ¨Çoading channel of each UE, and pt is the transmit power of each UE. At time t, the transmit power pt becomes effective immediately, while the other two elements in at
become effective when new tasks are started, i.e., after half-
completed tasks in the previous time frame are completed. Finally, we deÔ¨Åne reward rt. The expectation K(œÄ) in
problem (P2) is hard to obtain. Thus we use the number of completed tasks at the t-th time frame Kt(œÄ) as an estimate of K(œÄ). According to the problem deÔ¨Ånition in problem
(P2), we deÔ¨Åne the reward as:

rt

=

